snippet.textDisplay: Best guess on green to blue hair: The dye had a much higher concentration of blue pigment to yellow. Because she had yellowing at the roots/mid sections it helped even out the blue in the dye, making the top 2/3 of her hair appear green. This would explain why the ends, being white and porous, picked up a more blue hue.
snippet.textOriginal: Best guess on green to blue hair: The dye had a much higher concentration of blue pigment to yellow. Because she had yellowing at the roots/mid sections it helped even out the blue in the dye, making the top 2/3 of her hair appear green. This would explain why the ends, being white and porous, picked up a more blue hue.

snippet.textDisplay: For the first video, I can't "exactly" say why the ends turned blue, due to my not being a professional colorist but i just went pastel green/blue/teal and had a similar thing happen.  My theory is that because the ends were "whiter," they didn't have enough yellow to fully turn the color green like up top at her roots.  That is what contributed to my color variation with greener towards the roots and bluer towards the ends.  It may also be related to the heat from the scalp being necessary to process the yellow pigment in the dye since green is a mixture of blue and yellow.  Every time I've dyed my hair with any amount of a "blue" or cool colored dye it always takes to my hair faster and easier than any other color I'm putting my head, even purple, which has blue and a little bit of red in it.  I tend to like two tone hair though, since it's a bit more dynamic, so I'm almost always happy with my outcome.  I can understand why she might be unhappy with the lack of uniformity though if that's what she was aiming for.  (Edit: commented after the first video, so I did see you come to the same realization later in your video.  Also, I didn't use arctic fox for my color.  I used Ion color from Sally's and it worked similarly.)

snippet.textDisplay: The arctic fox green hair dye she used has a base blue pigment, since her ends were so porous and the blue pigment has a smaller molecule I think her hair just picked it up, also from looking closer her ends seem incredibly dry and rough looking so they wouldn't have  deposited color evenly either. That banding is such an easy fix with foils  heck a bleach bath would have been more efficient at that point, and they didnt seem to get all the pink completely out of her hair, an equalizer should have been used to help with the porosity.
snippet.textOriginal: The arctic fox green hair dye she used has a base blue pigment, since her ends were so porous and the blue pigment has a smaller molecule I think her hair just picked it up, also from looking closer her ends seem incredibly dry and rough looking so they wouldn't have  deposited color evenly either.
